00:29:12.900 --> 00:29:17.179
And so, the question of "What do you do if
you only have one minute?"

00:29:17.179 --> 00:29:22.690
I think it's different for different people.
And when I work with students one-on-one,

00:29:22.690 --> 00:29:27.420
it's kind of an exploration process to figure
out what's going to be the one yoga ritual

00:29:27.420 --> 00:29:30.640
that most makes you feel safe in your body
and in your mind.

00:29:30.640 --> 00:29:35.559
I think that's the -- sort of the starting
question point, because chronic pain is the

00:29:35.559 --> 00:29:38.720
experience of the body and brain not feeling
safe.

00:29:38.720 --> 00:29:44.100
And so, for some people it may be relaxation.
For some people, there may be a specific movement

00:29:44.100 --> 00:29:48.020
or stretch that makes their body feel really
good and cared for.

00:29:48.020 --> 00:29:50.920
For some people, mindfulness meditation works
really well.

00:29:50.920 --> 00:29:57.429
Just sitting down, being with the breath.
And it could be other things as well.

00:29:57.429 --> 00:30:02.860
So, in the book, I lay out lots of options.
And I encourage people to go to what they

00:30:02.860 --> 00:30:05.780
feel drawn to.
And as soon as you hear about it or read it

00:30:05.780 --> 00:30:11.130
and you think, "Well, that sounds kind of
appealing, not painful, not difficult -- might

00:30:11.130 --> 00:30:13.481
improve something about my state of mind or
body."

00:30:13.481 --> 00:30:16.150
And when you find something that works, to
stick with it.

00:30:16.150 --> 00:30:21.640
So I mentioned that a lot of the studies that
look at yoga for pain relief use all of these

00:30:21.640 --> 00:30:25.170
modalities.
And I'm not suggesting that you have to do

00:30:25.170 --> 00:30:29.050
all of them in order to feel the relief, but
I think in the group setting -- in a clinical

00:30:29.050 --> 00:30:33.360
setting -- you need to offer all of them,
because people will respond to different techniques

00:30:33.360 --> 00:30:37.880
and different practices.
But you yourself may find that it's sitting

00:30:37.880 --> 00:30:42.280
in meditation for a few minutes or that it's
a joint mobilization sequence.

00:30:42.280 --> 00:30:45.751
So I can't tell you exactly what to start
with.

00:30:45.751 --> 00:30:49.010
But I would say to start with where you're
naturally drawn.

00:30:49.010 --> 00:30:59.690
Q Hi. So you talk about this secondary pain
response where the injured part is not necessarily

00:30:59.690 --> 00:31:06.059
being damaged anymore but our brain is kind
of tricking us by sending the pain signal.

00:31:06.059 --> 00:31:07.059
A Mm-hmm.

00:31:07.059 --> 00:31:12.480
Q And so, my question is, how do you recognize
that that's the case, that that's happening,

00:31:12.480 --> 00:31:17.591
because it seems like -- to the brain it seems
like the same kind of pain.

00:31:17.591 --> 00:31:20.049
A Yeah, it's real.
And, of course, pain only happens in the brain.

00:31:20.049 --> 00:31:23.670
I mean, one of the things I want to be really
clear about is that this pain in the brain

00:31:23.670 --> 00:31:26.020
is real.
There's no other type of pain.

00:31:26.020 --> 00:31:30.500
And it doesn't matter whether it was generated
by someone punching you or something you can

00:31:30.500 --> 00:31:35.000
observe that's wrong with the body or whether
it started in the brain.

00:31:35.000 --> 00:31:40.340
It's just as real and just as painful.
You know, the way that most people start to

00:31:40.340 --> 00:31:44.620
realize that it's not about something that's
objectively wrong in the body anymore is by

00:31:44.620 --> 00:31:49.679
going through every test under the book and
trying surgery and finding that that doesn't

00:31:49.679 --> 00:31:53.610
work.
I mean, it's almost a trial and error, because

00:31:53.610 --> 00:31:56.250
many times, when people are in pain, there
is a physical problem.

00:31:56.250 --> 00:31:59.610
It could be cancer; it could be a joint issue
that could be repaired.

00:31:59.610 --> 00:32:05.559
And chronic pain is different than most of
those situations, because chronic pain is

00:32:05.559 --> 00:32:12.160
persistent and usually unexplainable.
And it's only -- you know, the mechanisms

00:32:12.160 --> 00:32:16.010
that I'm describing by which pain becomes
chronic -- it's not like doctors have good

00:32:16.010 --> 00:32:19.110
ways of diagnosing that.
A lot of that comes from animal research where,

00:32:19.110 --> 00:32:22.560
you know, they can really look at what's going
on in the nervous system.

00:32:22.560 --> 00:32:28.480
And so, there's not a great way for your doctor
to look at you and say, "Hey, that pain is

00:32:28.480 --> 00:32:32.610
starting in your brain."
Although, there are some researchers who are

00:32:32.610 --> 00:32:39.929
using real-time brain imaging to help show
patients how their pain is being created in

00:32:39.929 --> 00:32:42.809
the brain.
But that's not yet a clinical technique, so

00:32:42.809 --> 00:32:47.659
that wouldn't be useful for you.
But I would say that, if you have been exploring

00:32:47.659 --> 00:32:52.030
 -- through standard physical care -- the
source of your pain, and nobody can find anything

00:32:52.030 --> 00:32:57.200
 -- and that's what happens for a lot of people
 -- that's when exploring these other aspects

00:32:57.200 --> 00:32:59.940
like yoga and meditation may end up holding
the key.

00:32:59.940 --> 00:33:09.490
Q And so, when you recognize that that's the
case, what do you then do, because if your

00:33:09.490 --> 00:33:12.200
injured part is not hurting anymore per se.

00:33:12.200 --> 00:33:13.400
A Yeah. Yeah.

00:33:13.400 --> 00:33:14.900
Q The response probably should be different.

00:33:14.900 --> 00:33:20.670
A Right. And you start by retraining the response.
So, for example, breathing is a technique

00:33:20.670 --> 00:33:23.910
that changes the physiology of the body and
the brain pretty quickly.

00:33:23.910 --> 00:33:28.120
You can breathe in a way that's going to shut
down the stress response, lower inflammation.

00:33:28.120 --> 00:33:33.299
You can breathe in a way that's going to calm
down the emotional centers of the brain.

00:33:33.299 --> 00:33:37.180
And that's the essential training process
of yoga and meditation is, you work with the

00:33:37.180 --> 00:33:42.299
response and you practice a new response.
And you don't work with -- necessarily -- the

00:33:42.299 --> 00:33:46.090
area of the body that feels like it's in pain.
Most people, when they hear that I wrote a

00:33:46.090 --> 00:33:48.890
book about yoga for pain relief, they're like,
"Where's the chapter on neck pain?

00:33:48.890 --> 00:33:52.860
Where are the neck stretches for neck pain?
Where are the back stretches for back pain?"

00:33:52.860 --> 00:33:58.220
And that does not work with chronic pain,
because you can't fix a nervous system problem

00:33:58.220 --> 00:34:04.330
by just stretching out that part of the body.
And so, personally, I think that's good news,

00:34:04.330 --> 00:34:07.980
because it means, even if you don't know what's
causing your pain, you can start with the

00:34:07.980 --> 00:34:14.740
same basic practices of relaxation, simple
breath focus, and mindful movement of whatever

00:34:14.740 --> 00:34:20.580
part of your body can move without pain.
So I don't know if that's of any use.

00:34:20.580 --> 00:34:23.669
Q Yes, thank you.

00:34:23.669 --> 00:34:29.260
Q You know, yoga is a science, and it's got
many different branches.

00:34:29.260 --> 00:34:33.560
So I've been thinking of getting into yoga
and meditation for quite some time.

00:34:33.560 --> 00:34:38.960
And every time I kind of gotten to looking
at what I should be doing, I come up with

00:34:38.960 --> 00:34:45.481
various forms of yoga, like Kundalini and
Hatha and Astina and power yoga and then there

00:34:45.481 --> 00:34:49.670
are different forms of meditation.
And you know like Kundalini yoga says that,

00:34:49.670 --> 00:34:52.359
if you have back problem, you should not be
doing this.

00:34:52.359 --> 00:34:58.050
So, you know, how do you really get started
just as a basic person without getting to

00:34:58.050 --> 00:35:03.200
know that, you know, if I meditate.
Because somewhere I read that it takes you

00:35:03.200 --> 00:35:08.430
years before you can even reach to that one
second of meditative state where you do not

00:35:08.430 --> 00:35:10.960
have 500 thoughts crossing your mind in a
second.

00:35:10.960 --> 00:35:17.119
So, it's kind of, you know, demotivating as
well why you want to do it but then you just

00:35:17.119 --> 00:35:20.260
get confused by all that information that's
out there.

00:35:20.260 --> 00:35:23.791
So, how do you just get started without -- you
know?

00:35:23.791 --> 00:35:28.080
A Yeah. I can actually give a very specific
answer to that, and then, I'll give a more

00:35:28.080 --> 00:35:32.940
general response.
I actually almost always send people first

00:35:32.940 --> 00:35:36.420
to mindfulness-based stress reduction programs.
Some of you may have taken that.

00:35:36.420 --> 00:35:39.670
It's an 8-week course where you learn how
to focus on your breath.

00:35:39.670 --> 00:35:43.600
You learn the relaxation technique.
You learn very gentle yoga movements that

00:35:43.600 --> 00:35:48.810
are safe for most people.
And you learn some of the ideas of yoga philosophy

00:35:48.810 --> 00:35:55.580
and how they relate to everyday life.
And even though it tends to be considered

00:35:55.580 --> 00:36:00.210
a meditation training, because it involves
movement and breathing and relaxation and

00:36:00.210 --> 00:36:03.560
yoga philosophy, it's like the perfect introduction
to yoga.

00:36:03.560 --> 00:36:08.441
And I know they offer NBSR all over the Bay
Area -- I think, probably even offer it here.

00:36:08.441 --> 00:36:09.441
Does Google have --?

00:36:09.441 --> 00:36:10.570
Q They're starting next week.

00:36:10.570 --> 00:36:12.119
A It's starting next week?

00:36:12.119 --> 00:36:13.119
Q Yep. Yep.

00:36:13.119 --> 00:36:15.060
A There -- I think so.
I actually think that's going to be a really

00:36:15.060 --> 00:36:17.950
great introduction.
And they will, I think, quickly disabuse you

00:36:17.950 --> 00:36:22.420
of the notion that it's going to take millions
of years to achieve meditation.

00:36:22.420 --> 00:36:27.109
You know, with meditation, you don't even
need to empty the mind or clear your thoughts.

00:36:27.109 --> 00:36:33.119
You can just -- you can have one moment of
breath focus in a 10-minute meditation, and

00:36:33.119 --> 00:36:38.470
that in itself can be healing.
So, you can get benefit much sooner than it

00:36:38.470 --> 00:36:43.520
takes to become a monk.
And the other thing that I'll say is that,

00:36:43.520 --> 00:36:49.520
one of the most encouraging things about the
research on yoga for pain is that they're

00:36:49.520 --> 00:36:56.099
almost always looking at people who had no
yoga or meditation experience and saw these

00:36:56.099 --> 00:37:00.320
 -- not just statistically significant, but
clinically significant -- improvements in

00:37:00.320 --> 00:37:03.580
8 weeks.
These aren't very long interventions.

00:37:03.580 --> 00:37:05.200
And so, you know, I think that there's hope.

00:37:05.200 --> 00:37:06.510
Q Thanks.

00:37:06.510 --> 00:37:12.450
Q Just adding to this discussion that was
happening.

00:37:12.450 --> 00:37:18.810
I am a yoga teacher, and I've had an experience
of teaching yoga back in India, practicing

00:37:18.810 --> 00:37:25.350
yoga there and practicing yoga here.
And I have found a very big difference in

00:37:25.350 --> 00:37:29.369
the U.S. -- the way you always talk about
yoga and meditation together.

00:37:29.369 --> 00:37:33.340
In the U.S., there is this whole big thing
of looking at yoga as another form of exercise.

00:37:33.340 --> 00:37:37.859
It's like, you know, power yoga -- and I think
some of the injuries are created here, because

00:37:37.859 --> 00:37:43.380
there is so much of emphasis on totally the
physical part -- looking it as just like another

00:37:43.380 --> 00:37:47.750
form of exercise.
And the way to enter yoga is to understand

00:37:47.750 --> 00:37:51.660
it holistically -- body, mind, breath.
Like the way you said, the meditation part

00:37:51.660 --> 00:37:54.030
is not to be neglected.
The philosophy is not to be neglected.

00:37:54.030 --> 00:37:58.180
And only then, yoga provides this healing
process, the whole.

00:37:58.180 --> 00:38:03.300
It's innate in it, you know?
But I feel that it's kind of neglected here.

00:38:03.300 --> 00:38:07.040
But the perspective in India is totally different
from it.

00:38:07.040 --> 00:38:09.859
A Yeah, and that's really the traditional
perspective.

00:38:09.859 --> 00:38:14.560
And thank God most of the studies are actually
looking at the traditional yoga rather than

00:38:14.560 --> 00:38:20.600
super fit "yoga butt" yoga.
And that's not where I would send someone

00:38:20.600 --> 00:38:25.410
initially.
Although physical exercise is really, really

00:38:25.410 --> 00:38:32.000
important, but sometimes yoga classes that
are presenting yoga as a hard-core workout

00:38:32.000 --> 00:38:37.109
really lose the elements of relaxation and
breathing that make it so healing for chronic

00:38:37.109 --> 00:38:39.470
pain.
So, exercise is important, but I definitely

00:38:39.470 --> 00:38:44.640
would not start with any form of yoga that
was advertising itself primarily as a workout.

00:38:44.640 --> 00:38:55.650
You would miss a lot and possibly hurt yourself.

00:38:55.650 --> 00:39:00.960
Q Can you comment on the connection between
yoga and diet?

00:39:00.960 --> 00:39:07.090
A Yoga and diet -- yes.
Well, in the yoga tradition, what you eat

00:39:07.090 --> 00:39:12.540
is considered both a reflection of your willingness
to care for your own body and an expression

00:39:12.540 --> 00:39:15.650
of your values.
So, you know, within the yoga tradition, it's

00:39:15.650 --> 00:39:21.690
common to eat the kind of diet that Michael
Pollan might approve of -- mostly plants and

00:39:21.690 --> 00:39:25.780
real food and not a whole lot of it or whatever
his -- what are his rules?

00:39:25.780 --> 00:39:29.660
Says, you know, mostly -- eat mostly plants
and fruits and vegetables.

00:39:29.660 --> 00:39:33.869
Don't eat too much.
I think that that's the essential yoga diet.

00:39:33.869 --> 00:39:41.160
And there's some good evidence that eating
a mostly plant-based diet, possibly a vegetarian

00:39:41.160 --> 00:39:45.850
diet, changes the way that the body responds
to stress, improving things like heart rate

00:39:45.850 --> 00:39:49.730
variability and inflammation.
That could be really important for chronic

00:39:49.730 --> 00:39:54.090
pain and chronic stress.
Now, I'm personally a vegan.

00:39:54.090 --> 00:39:57.001
So I always feel like I'm proselytizing a
little bit when I say that.

00:39:57.001 --> 00:40:02.660
So, let me just say that, you can go much
more broad than that and not worry about the

00:40:02.660 --> 00:40:07.970
traditional diet and just think of -- starting
to pay attention to how "what you eat" influences

00:40:07.970 --> 00:40:12.109
your energy, how it influences your mood,
how it even influences your pain.

00:40:12.109 --> 00:40:16.180
Because many people will find that they have
triggers -- food triggers -- for being in

00:40:16.180 --> 00:40:18.490
a bad mood.
Not what you eat when you are in a bad mood,

00:40:18.490 --> 00:40:21.349
but food that actually puts you in a worse
mood -- makes you feel worse about yourself,

00:40:21.349 --> 00:40:25.920
it makes your body feel sluggish and tired.
And so, yeah, you know -- without any sort

00:40:25.920 --> 00:40:30.310
of moral judgments about what you might eat,
there's this basic practice of starting to

00:40:30.310 --> 00:40:35.849
pay attention to how food influences you and
a willingness to take care of yourself by

00:40:35.849 --> 00:40:38.310
eating what makes you feel healthier and stronger.

00:40:38.310 --> 00:40:50.260
Q How about yoga and other form of exercises,
you know?

00:40:50.260 --> 00:40:54.710
If I practice yoga, is there other form of
exercise that are more compatible or they

00:40:54.710 --> 00:40:59.130
are not compatible?
Any concern about that?

00:40:59.130 --> 00:41:03.420
A Yeah. So, the question is, "Are there other
forms of exercise that are more or less compatible

00:41:03.420 --> 00:41:07.510
with yoga?"
And, I think, the way that I would express

00:41:07.510 --> 00:41:15.980
it is that, once you learn how to move skillfully
and honor your body in yoga, it's going to

00:41:15.980 --> 00:41:19.599
improve your experience in any other form
of exercise -- whether it's weight lifting

00:41:19.599 --> 00:41:25.109
or swimming or dancing.
And so, I would say more that, learning how

00:41:25.109 --> 00:41:31.890
to listen to your body through yoga, to not
push yourself beyond what seems like a reasonable

00:41:31.890 --> 00:41:37.820
limit, to listen to the signals of your body
about fatigue and stretch and pain, and a

00:41:37.820 --> 00:41:41.240
kind of willingness to stay in the process
mentally.

00:41:41.240 --> 00:41:45.700
All of that is going to make other forms of
exercise not just more fun, but a lot safer.

00:41:45.700 --> 00:41:48.720
So if you learn how to do those things in
yoga, you're going to be much less likely

00:41:48.720 --> 00:41:54.109
to hurt yourself if you go to an aerobics
class or play a sport.

00:41:54.109 --> 00:41:58.040
And I have a number of students who are athletes
who kind of use their yoga practice in that

00:41:58.040 --> 00:42:02.830
way as a kind of baseline so that when they
go out and do other things, they're less likely

00:42:02.830 --> 00:42:06.200
to hurt themselves.
In terms of the physical benefits, yoga is

00:42:06.200 --> 00:42:09.480
not cardiovascular.
So if you are thinking about your health,

00:42:09.480 --> 00:42:14.410
the only way to get a really strong cardiovascular
workout from yoga is to do it wrong.

00:42:14.410 --> 00:42:18.070
To, you know -- to not breathe in a slow and
sustained way.

00:42:18.070 --> 00:42:21.310
Because, even if you're doing things that
are a little bit physically difficult, if

00:42:21.310 --> 00:42:26.060
you're breathing in the yoga way, you're not
going to get your heart rate that high.

00:42:26.060 --> 00:42:31.710
There's plenty of studies showing that.
So, it's nice to balance yoga with other forms

00:42:31.710 --> 00:42:38.880
of exercise that are appropriate for your
body that would take care of that other stuff.

00:42:38.880 --> 00:42:43.340
&gt;&gt; All right. Well, I think that wraps up
our questions.

00:42:43.340 --> 00:42:44.960
So, thank you very much.
It was an outstanding talk.

00:42:44.960 --> 00:42:45.960
Thank you.

00:42:45.960 --> 00:42:47.430
A Thanks.

00:42:47.430 --> 00:42:49.670
[Applause]

00:42:49.670 --> 00:42:54.860
&gt;&gt; Kelly: So, I see we have about 15 minutes
left.

00:42:54.860 --> 00:43:01.010
Do you want to do a little bit of a practice?
Yes?

00:43:01.010 --> 00:43:05.119
I'd thought that we would do some movement,
some breathing, some relaxation, and meditation.

00:43:05.119 --> 00:43:10.880
It's kind of an unusual spot to lie down on
the ground and meditate.

00:43:10.880 --> 00:43:15.290
So, let's start with movement and that may
be -- movement and breathing -- and that may

00:43:15.290 --> 00:43:21.800
be as far as we get.
I'm going to -- [pause] Yeah, so I'll use

00:43:21.800 --> 00:43:26.840
this mic.
And we're going to start in a chair -- how

00:43:26.840 --> 00:43:30.260
convenient.
But I want you to have a little more space

00:43:30.260 --> 00:43:36.080
for yourself.
So, these chairs move. You can move your chair.

00:43:36.080 --> 00:43:41.050
Maybe come -- those of you who are sandwiched
in a row, there's a lot of room up front,

00:43:41.050 --> 00:43:42.290
a lot of chairs up front -- you could come
up here.

00:43:42.290 --> 00:43:47.910
This is going to be interesting to demonstrate
and hold this at the same time.

00:43:47.910 --> 00:43:52.880
Oh, that's right. That's what the stand is
for. [pause]

00:43:52.880 --> 00:44:14.440
I feel like I'm on "American Idol." [pause]
Is that going to be about the right, no -- is

00:44:14.440 --> 00:44:21.850
that about the right sound volume?
Okay, so we're going to be efficient with

00:44:21.850 --> 00:44:28.360
this and move and breathe at the same time.
You were probably already breathing, but you

00:44:28.360 --> 00:44:31.951
might not have noticed.
So we're going to breathe with some intention

00:44:31.951 --> 00:44:35.741
here.
And some of the key ideas about yoga movement

00:44:35.741 --> 00:44:41.330
and breathing is, first of all, it should
feel better -- not worse -- than if you were

00:44:41.330 --> 00:44:46.400
not doing it.
So, as soon as something feels obviously worse

00:44:46.400 --> 00:44:51.099
than before you started, come out of it.
There may be a way to come back into it with

00:44:51.099 --> 00:44:54.700
a little bit less strain.
You know, sort of relax a little bit in it.

00:44:54.700 --> 00:44:57.920
Or it may be that this is not the movement
or stretch for you in this moment and be willing

00:44:57.920 --> 00:45:02.720
to honor that.
The other key principle is that, we join the

00:45:02.720 --> 00:45:07.349
movement and the breath.
So if we're doing a movement with the breath,

00:45:07.349 --> 00:45:10.870
let the breath guide the movement, rather
than for example, if we were -- we're going

00:45:10.870 --> 00:45:14.330
to take a movement where we move the spine
with the breath.

00:45:14.330 --> 00:45:19.890
This would be the movement of the inhale;
this would be the movement of the exhale.

00:45:19.890 --> 00:45:27.060
You wouldn't want to move and then breathe
and then move and then remember to breathe.

00:45:27.060 --> 00:45:30.359
There's really no difference between the movement
of the body and the movement of the breath.

00:45:30.359 --> 00:45:33.700
So just work with those ideas.
It shouldn't be worse than if you weren't

00:45:33.700 --> 00:45:37.010
doing it, and we're going to link the movement
to the body and the breath.

00:45:37.010 --> 00:45:39.020
So let's start perched a little bit forward
on the chair.

00:45:39.020 --> 00:45:42.950
If you're way slid back, come forward.
Let your feet be flat on the ground.

00:45:42.950 --> 00:45:47.880
Anyone who wants to take their shoes off,
you're welcome to do that.

00:45:47.880 --> 00:45:51.390
Legs comfortably apart.
And take a moment to lift your shoulders up

00:45:51.390 --> 00:45:54.290
to your ears.
Some of you already have them there.

00:45:54.290 --> 00:45:58.599
And then, drop them down.
And let's do that with an open-mouth exhalation.

00:45:58.599 --> 00:46:04.150
Inhale -- lift your shoulders up to your ears.
Exhale -- relax and down.

00:46:04.150 --> 00:46:06.760
One more time.
Let the shoulder blades drop even a little

00:46:06.760 --> 00:46:13.220
more. [exhaling]
And let them kind of rest in this place with

00:46:13.220 --> 00:46:17.460
the hands on the thighs or on the knees.
And, on your inhalation, draw the shoulders

00:46:17.460 --> 00:46:23.430
back, lift the chest, look up a little bit.
And, as you exhale, put it in reverse -- draw

00:46:23.430 --> 00:46:30.380
your belly in, drop your chin a little bit.
And continue with your breath -- inhale, lift

00:46:30.380 --> 00:46:38.240
the chest; exhale, curve the back.
Keep it going at your pace.

00:46:38.240 --> 00:46:42.820
And notice how the movement actually helps
extend the breath a little bit if you're patient.

00:46:42.820 --> 00:46:47.080
When you round the back and pull the belly
in, it helps push the breath out.

00:46:47.080 --> 00:46:51.310
When you lift the chest and relax the belly,
it creates a little more space for the breath

00:46:51.310 --> 00:47:07.099
if you're patient.
Take maybe two more breaths in this way. [breathing]

00:47:07.099 --> 00:47:11.200
And then, finish with the spine feeling pretty
neutral here.

00:47:11.200 --> 00:47:17.790
Bring one hand to the belly -- maybe both
hands to the belly -- and either close your

00:47:17.790 --> 00:47:22.940
eyes or just drop your gaze a little bit.
And now, connect to the sensation of the belly

00:47:22.940 --> 00:47:26.860
moving when you breathe.
If you're patient and your pants aren't too

00:47:26.860 --> 00:47:34.210
tight, you will probably find that your belly
expands when you breathe in and it draws in

00:47:34.210 --> 00:47:38.720
when you breathe out.
And let's take a few more breaths, resting

00:47:38.720 --> 00:47:46.540
the mind in the sensation of what expands
 -- feeling the sensation of expansion as

00:47:46.540 --> 00:48:00.920
you "breathe in" and the sensation of that
expansion dissolving as you "breathe out."

00:48:00.920 --> 00:48:03.630
And then, open your eyes.
So with that, we did movement, breathing,

00:48:03.630 --> 00:48:07.790
and meditation in just a couple of minutes.
That first movement helped release tension

00:48:07.790 --> 00:48:11.030
in the belly and the back.
That helps release tension in the breath.

00:48:11.030 --> 00:48:15.140
Next movement is going to help release tension
in the side of the body to also release tension

00:48:15.140 --> 00:48:17.660
in the breath.
So, we're going to take the legs a little

00:48:17.660 --> 00:48:22.839
wider apart if you've got the space for that.
And again, kind of scoot forward on your chair.

00:48:22.839 --> 00:48:28.310
Let your left hand rest on your left thigh,
and you might even slide down to your elbow.

00:48:28.310 --> 00:48:34.599
Notice how just that movement lengthened the
right side of your body.

00:48:34.599 --> 00:48:39.119
That's already a stretch.
Bonus -- if you like -- inhale, take the right

00:48:39.119 --> 00:48:42.720
arm up.
Notice that's a deeper stretch.

00:48:42.720 --> 00:48:46.750
Are we in the zone now of "It still feels
better," or did that make it worse?

00:48:46.750 --> 00:48:51.220
If it made it worse, you can lower the arm
down and relax your head in whatever direction

00:48:51.220 --> 00:48:53.961
feels best.
If it feels better to have that right arm

00:48:53.961 --> 00:48:58.580
reaching, do it with some intention.
Reach out through the fingers.

00:48:58.580 --> 00:49:03.160
Feel the length in the side of your body,
and make a conscious choice to position your

00:49:03.160 --> 00:49:07.310
head and neck in a way that feels sustainable.
If you had to be here for a little while,

00:49:07.310 --> 00:49:13.859
what would be the position of least tension,
least likely to leave you feeling worse than

00:49:13.859 --> 00:49:17.980
when we started?
And on your next inhale, come all the way

00:49:17.980 --> 00:49:23.260
up and exhale -- release the arm down.
Take a simple breath in.

00:49:23.260 --> 00:49:27.030
And, on your next exhalation, lean onto the
right arm.

00:49:27.030 --> 00:49:33.940
Notice that subtle stretch, that subtle stretch.
And on an inhale, you can reach the left arm

00:49:33.940 --> 00:49:42.560
up, and stay here for a few breaths.
Again, using the reach of the arm to improve

00:49:42.560 --> 00:49:48.420
the sensation of opening.
And you might even have the idea of breathing

00:49:48.420 --> 00:49:55.599
into the left side of your rib cage and waist.
If you just plant that idea, you may find

00:49:55.599 --> 00:49:59.720
that, if you inhale deeply, you can increase
the stretch from the inside out.

00:49:59.720 --> 00:50:05.000
There's a sensation of expanding underneath
the muscles that are stretching.

00:50:05.000 --> 00:50:11.619
One last breath here.
And, on an inhale, come all the way up.

00:50:11.619 --> 00:50:14.570
Exhale -- release that arm down.
You can walk your legs together.

00:50:14.570 --> 00:50:17.240
And now, let's bring our hands to the side
of the body.

00:50:17.240 --> 00:50:22.060
The ribs -- and whatever way is most comfortable
 -- to find that part of your body.

00:50:22.060 --> 00:50:27.400
And again, close your eyes or drop your gaze.
So it's easier for the mind to drop into the

00:50:27.400 --> 00:50:32.900
breath.
And now, have the idea that, if you're patient,

00:50:32.900 --> 00:50:38.550
the breath might expand the body where your
hands are resting.

00:50:38.550 --> 00:50:43.550
Invite the possibility of some side-to-side
expansion when you breathe in without trying

00:50:43.550 --> 00:50:51.180
to force it.
And let the mind rest in this feeling -- the

00:50:51.180 --> 00:51:00.970
sensation.
As you do so, relaxing the forehead, relaxing

00:51:00.970 --> 00:51:09.550
your eyes, relaxing the jaw if there's any
clenching, and then open the eyes.

00:51:09.550 --> 00:51:14.900
Relax your arms down.
And then, the next movement or stretch is

00:51:14.900 --> 00:51:18.109
going to help release tension in the neck
and the shoulder.

00:51:18.109 --> 00:51:23.660
And you even have muscles in your neck and
in your shoulder that are involved in breathing.

00:51:23.660 --> 00:51:28.820
When they're tense, they can turn your breath
into a kind of "up and down," shallow breath.

00:51:28.820 --> 00:51:33.400
And by relaxing them, it can allow the natural
movement of the breath in a way that's not

00:51:33.400 --> 00:51:37.080
quite so stressful and inefficient.
So for this -- very simple -- drop your left

00:51:37.080 --> 00:51:44.320
ear to your left shoulder.
And notice if you are pulling your ear to

00:51:44.320 --> 00:51:46.310
your shoulder with your neck muscles, that's
too much.

00:51:46.310 --> 00:51:52.070
We don't need that much tension.
Just drop the head and let gravity hold you

00:51:52.070 --> 00:51:56.550
in this posture.
Gravity can help you on the right side -- the

00:51:56.550 --> 00:51:59.980
right arm.
By dropping the arm heavy alongside your outer

00:51:59.980 --> 00:52:05.560
leg or even hooking on and holding onto the
chair if there's some place easy to do that.

00:52:05.560 --> 00:52:10.560
And let the weight of the arm bone be heavy
and the weight of your head heavy.

00:52:10.560 --> 00:52:16.980
And take another couple of breaths resting
in the sensation along the side of your neck,

00:52:16.980 --> 00:52:24.420
the front of the shoulder and chest.
Smiling sometimes improves the sensation of

00:52:24.420 --> 00:52:31.010
the stretch, because the muscles here connect
to the side of your face.

00:52:31.010 --> 00:52:36.020
And on an inhale, come all the way up.
Before we do the other side, simply place

00:52:36.020 --> 00:52:41.520
your left hand on the right side of your chest
underneath the collarbone -- underneath where

00:52:41.520 --> 00:52:46.050
you were stretching.
And have the idea that there might be some

00:52:46.050 --> 00:52:51.290
expansion of the breath under the hand here.
This is more likely to be a subtle expansion

00:52:51.290 --> 00:52:54.460
of the breath.
And it doesn't involve lifting your shoulders

00:52:54.460 --> 00:52:59.510
up to your ears.
If you close your eyes and drop your gaze,

00:52:59.510 --> 00:53:04.490
see if there's a kind of massage that's happening
in this area of the easy, subtle expansion

00:53:04.490 --> 00:53:14.200
of the lungs as you breathe in, and the release
of that expansion as you breathe out.

00:53:14.200 --> 00:53:22.230
As if the lungs and the heart's gently expanding
 -- gently swelling with the breath.

00:53:22.230 --> 00:53:28.430
And open your eyes, relax your arms.
And let's even that off.

00:53:28.430 --> 00:53:34.760
Take the second side, dropping your right
ear to your right shoulder.

00:53:34.760 --> 00:53:38.560
And again, there's a real difference between
trying to pull the ear and shoulder together

00:53:38.560 --> 00:53:43.440
with your neck muscles and shoulder muscles
 -- versus, once you've tilted, let it go.

00:53:43.440 --> 00:53:48.310
Let gravity drop the weight of the head.
And your left arm can hang down by your side,

00:53:48.310 --> 00:53:52.220
or hook into the chair if that feels more
supportive.

00:53:52.220 --> 00:53:57.170
And you can even experiment here with how
much the chin is "tucked down" versus "lifted

00:53:57.170 --> 00:54:00.000
up."
It's a big difference.

00:54:00.000 --> 00:54:05.700
And you can find the position -- the angle
of the chin -- that feels best to you to what's

00:54:05.700 --> 00:54:10.070
needed in this moment.
And see, there's a way to enjoy the sensation.

00:54:10.070 --> 00:54:16.339
We sometimes interpret stretch as pain, but
this is probably a safe movement for you and

00:54:16.339 --> 00:54:19.869
maybe even a healing movement.
So, see if there's a way to interpret it in

00:54:19.869 --> 00:54:28.339
that way -- enjoy how it feels. [pause]
And on an inhalation, bring the head back

00:54:28.339 --> 00:54:31.640
up to center.
And then, take your right hand, rest it on

00:54:31.640 --> 00:54:39.190
the left side of the chest.
And close your eyes, or drop your gaze.

00:54:39.190 --> 00:54:44.150
And invite the possibility that this part
of the body will also have a nice rhythmic

00:54:44.150 --> 00:54:56.359
expansion and release as you breathe.
This is one of my favorite meditations -- hands-on

00:54:56.359 --> 00:55:02.640
breathing.
It gives the mind something to focus on; helps

00:55:02.640 --> 00:55:08.070
relax the body.
Go ahead and open your eyes if they're closed.

00:55:08.070 --> 00:55:10.609
And let's take one last stretch.
This will be for the front of the chest.

00:55:10.609 --> 00:55:14.609
You can bring your hands to the back of your
chair.

00:55:14.609 --> 00:55:21.180
And, you know, depending on your shoulders
and how tight your jacket is, reaching on

00:55:21.180 --> 00:55:25.060
top of the chair might feel better or reaching
along the side of the chair might feel better,

00:55:25.060 --> 00:55:31.060
and see which is true for you.
And then, just kind of hang the rib cage forward.

00:55:31.060 --> 00:55:34.890
And the head can rest in a neutral position.
And you're not looking for the world's biggest

00:55:34.890 --> 00:55:38.310
stretch here.
This is a shape change -- the spine is moving

00:55:38.310 --> 00:55:43.290
into the body -- the chest is being opened
as the arms are pulled back, and whether you're

00:55:43.290 --> 00:55:47.750
feeling a lot or whether you're feeling a
very subtle stretch, you can kind of trust

00:55:47.750 --> 00:55:48.750
this process.

00:55:48.750 --> 00:56:04.470
And see if you can feel the expansion of the
breath and your rib cage and chest.

00:56:04.470 --> 00:56:09.940
And then, relax back to center.
And rest your hands over your heart, underneath

00:56:09.940 --> 00:56:15.079
the collarbones.
And again, you can drop your gaze or close

00:56:15.079 --> 00:56:19.109
your eyes.
And invite the possibility that this area

00:56:19.109 --> 00:56:35.910
of the body will also expand gently when you
breathe in and sink as you breathe out. [pause]

00:56:35.910 --> 00:56:43.290
And each time this area sinks -- each time
the heart sinks -- imagine any last bit of

00:56:43.290 --> 00:56:48.730
stress or tension exiting the body.

00:56:48.730 --> 00:56:59.160
And then, go ahead and open your eyes. Okay.
So, that was a little meditation, breathing,

00:56:59.160 --> 00:57:03.570
movement all at once -- something you can
